Commentary.Commentary: Now though, they will need to put this behind and concentrate on their batting. They have an uphill task ahead of them as this wicket is offering quite a bit for the spinners and Pakistan have two. England will not want to concede a good lead to Pakistan and the away side would love one. It is about surviving the remainder of the day without a lot of damage. Can they do so? We will find out in a while.

The England bowling, on both the days, was brilliant to begin with! However, after the Lunch break, they looked flat. Their pacers looked ineffective and Bess was very unfortunate. He did create chances but he was let down by Buttler. One of those were of Masood which cost England really badly. Overall, it was a below average performance by the hosts.

Pakistan have ended with a total which is more than competitive! They will be pretty pleased with where they stand in the game at the moment. They have one man to thank and that is Shan Masood. He was the mainstay! Yes, he was supported by Shadab and Azam but his innings could well prove to be the difference. Also, just the two 100-plus stands is what took Pakistan to a very good total. There was not a lot of contribution from the rest. Overall though, it will be the visitors who are happier after this innings.

They would hope to take the remaining two wickets as quickly as possible or 350 is going to be a daunting total. Stay tuned for an important session coming up after the Tea break.

It all went wrong for Pakistan! Yes, England bowled really well but the visitors did not show a lot of intent and were content in defending or leaving most of the deliveries. The day itself started off poorly for them as they lost Azam early. Shafiq and Rizwan did not contribute a lot but Masood is hanging in there. A lot relies on him now and they would hope Shadab can provide able support as there is not a lot of batting to come. 250 is what they will be aiming for right now. Can they get there? We should find out in the next session. Do join us at 1340 Local (1240 GMT) for the Post-Lunch session.

The three were very disciplined, gave absolutely nothing away, they were also patient and that patience was rewarded with three good wickets. They are now into the bowling all-rounders and they would hope they can bag the remaining 5 wickets as quickly as possible.

Another defensive stroke! This is played away from the body but this time it is done well. However, it is quite risky in England. You need to play it late and close to the body.

Back of a length and on off, defended.

Fullish ball on off, Rizwan prods forward and blocks it to the off side. Pakistan last scored a run in the 54th over.
On a length on off, Mohammad blocks it to cover.
BEATEN! Lovely bowling from Woakes! This was a loose shot though! Full delivery outside off, Rizwan pushes at it but fails to get any bat on it.
Chris Woakes is into the attack for the first time on Day 2. 8-2-14-1 are his figures so far.
Outside off again, left alone. Another maiden over. 6 in a row for England. Pakistan are playing themselves into a shell here.
Very full and outside off, Anderson is looking to tempt Masood into a drive. The opener resists and lets it be.
Shorter and on off, Masood guides it to point.
One more ball outside off, Masood lets it go.
Outside off, Masood need not play at those.
Back of a length and on middle, kept out.
Once again makes the batter play by attacking the stumps. Rizwan negotiates it well. Good three balls to end.
On the stumps, Rizwan gets right behind the line and defends it.

NOT OUT! There is a spike on Ultra Edge! Just a feather probably which only Rizwan must have felt and hence, he reviewed. A good one though and the Pakistan side will breathe a big sigh of relief. Another wicket would have been dreadful for them right now. Broad lands it on middle, it is on a length. Rizwan goes back to defend but it straightens. It seems to have missed the bat and hit the pad. An appeal and up goes the finger. Rizwan reviews immediately. Replays roll in and it shows the on-field call has to be overturned.
Mohammad Rizwan has been given out LBW. He has reviewed it immediately. The Ultra Edge rolls in and it shows that there is bat involved. Excellent review.
One more delivery outside off, not played at. There have been quite a few deliveries which have been outside off.
Into the off pole now, Rizwan solidly keeps it out.
Watchful leave! This is just outside off, not played at.
A harmless delivery to end! Outside off, Masood shoulders arms to this one. Another maiden.

Change of angle from Anderson and it nearly worked! Angles it into the off pole and then gets it to straighten. Masood is squared up as he tries to block. It goes off the outside edge but on the bounce to gully. Masood played it with soft hands.
Once again keeps it outside off, it is not fiddled with.
Wide outside off, left alone.
That is a gem! Beats the outside edge! It is on a length and around off, angles away late. Masood is drawn into playing at it. He ends up pushing at it away from the body. Gets beaten.
Good length and on off, Masood defends it.
A wicket maiden from Broad! Brilliant. On off, Rizwan defends it onto the ground.
Mohammad Rizwan makes his way out to the middle.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Broad now gets one! Asad Shafiq walks back for a single digit score and England are probably back on top in this game. This is a lovely delivery. It is on a length, it lands around off and then straightens a touch. There is also good bounce on this one. Asad looks to defend but does so inside the line. It flies off the outside edge and goes towards second slip where Stokes makes no mistake. England have started brilliantly today morning.
Slightly fuller this time and on off, Shafiq pushes it towards mid off.
Good length delivery on the off pole, Shafiq gets right behind the line and keeps it out.
On off, Shafiq lunges and keeps it out.
Outside off, not played at.

Fuller and on off, Masood strokes it to mid off.
Goes back to bowling outside off, another leave. Good carry for Anderson. Buttler takes it near his chest.
Closer to the off pole but the length is shorter. Masood goes back and keeps it out easily.

Outside off, left alone.
Good length delivery outside off, Shafiq watches the ball carefully and leaves it alone.

Good length ball outside off, Shafiq leaves it alone.

Good length ball on middle, Shafiq strides forward and defends it to mid off.
Some sawdust is being put on the bowler's crease.
Outside off, Masood does not bother playing at that.
Good running! Length ball on off, Shafiq blocks it to cover and takes a quick single. Broad comes ahead and throws it to the keeper's end but misses. Masood was in though. 150 up for Pakistan.
On a length on off, Shafiq is solid in defense.
BEATEN! Anderson has been right on the money on Day 2. He was poor on Day 1. Good length ball outside off, Shafiq looks to defend but fails to get any bat on it.
Full on middle, Asad blocks it to mid on for a dot.
Good length ball on off, Shafiq prods forward and defends it to the cover region.
Nicely bowled! Good length ball around off, nipping in. Masood attempts to defend it but misses out and gets hit on the pads.

FIFTY! 7th Test fifty for Masood! He struggled at the start but he stuck it out and now has reached his fifty. Brilliant. Back of a length ball outside off, Masood punches it through the cover region and picks up a couple to get to the milestone. Can he continue on and score a big one?
Full delivery on middle, Masood flicks it to deep mid-wicket and picks up a couple.

NOT OUT! There is bat involved! England lose a review! It did not look he had hit it but the replays prove otherwise! Broad bowls a good length ball on off, angling in. Masood looks to defend but seems to have missed. It raps him on his pads and England put up an appeal. The umpire is not interested. Root takes the review after a brief discussion with his teammates and opts for it. The Ultra Edge rolls in and it shows that there is a spike as the ball passed the bat. Great decision by the umpire.
Review time! England have taken a review for LBW. Shan Masood is the man in question. It looks close. The Ultra Edge rolls in and it shows that there is bat on it. Review lost.
On a good length and outside off, Masood leaves it alone.
Asad Shafiq is the next man in. Stuart Broad will bowl from the other end.

OUT! CAUGHT! That's what England would have been hoping for at the start! Brilliant delivery from James Anderson. Azam goes after playing a classy knock. England needed this start after having a poor Day 1. Anderson dishes a full delivery outside off, moving away. Azam looks to drive it. It takes the outside edge and goes to Root at first slip who makes no mistake. Anderson was testing Azam in this over and gave away no freebies and he has been rewarded for his tight line and length.
Fullish ball on middle, Babar solidly defends it to mid-wicket.

Excellent start from James Anderson! He bowls a good length ball on off, moving away. Azam looks to defend but the ball beats the outside edge, hits the thigh pad and rolls to the slip cordon.

Right then! The rain has stopped and we are having a prompt start. The England players make their way out to the middle, followed by Shan Masood and Babar Azam. 98 overs are scheduled to be bowled in the day, weather permitting. James Anderson will start with the ball for the hosts.

Weather report - There is a slight drizzle going on in Manchester but there is still around 30 minutes to go for the scheduled start. The weather is forecasted to be better than Day 1. Let's hope that the rain blows away and we have a prompt start.

Welcome everyone! A shortened Day 1 belonged to Pakistan, with Babar Azam looking at his best. Shan Masood was given two lives by Jos Buttler but full credit should be given to the Pakistani batter for sticking it out in the middle. On Day 2, Pakistan would look to continue the good work and post a good score on the board. England, on the other hand, started well with the ball but went flat after Lunch to give Pakistan the advantage. They need to perform much better with the ball and pick up quick wickets to regain some control. Will Pakistan continue to impress or will England make a comeback?
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Pakistan will hope that they can bat long and set the base for them to score a big first innings total. England, on the other hand, were poor with the ball and they need to break this stand quickly. A big total by Pakistan in the first innings is not what they want as the visitors have two spinners and the hosts have to bat last on this wicket. An important first session awaits us on Day 2. Also, the weather is a lot better on Thursday. Do join us at 1100 Local (1000 GMT) for the second day's play. Until then, cheers and take care.

Pakistan's day in the end! The stand between Masood and Azam has given them the advantage. They were in trouble when they lost both the Alis but a stand which is just 4 short of a ton has taken them to safer shores. Babar Azam and Shan Masood have played the bowlers with ease and are looking comfortable in the middle.
So the inevitable has happened! It is STUMPS on Day 1! Just the 49 overs were manageable today but we got to witness some good Test match action in those overs.

The umpires have checked for bad light and they deem the conditions unfit to play cricket. They are taking the players off. Root is having a discussion with the umpires but he has to go back. Probably that will be the end of the day.

Welcome back! All set for the game to resume after a long rain break. The England players make their way out to the middle, followed by Babar Azam and Shan Masood. Jofra Archer will finish his over. 22.5 overs are scheduled to be bowled with Stumps at 1900 Local (1800 GMT).

Update 1735 Local (1635 GMT) - Great news, the inspections are done and we have a restart time. The action resumes at 1745 Local (1645 GMT). It has been a long, long wait but it will be pleasing to see play resume.

Update 1710 Local (1610 GMT) - The umpires have done their inspection and it looks like they are still not happy with the ground conditions. Another inspection is scheduled for 1730 Local (1630 GMT). Stay tuned.
Update 1635 Local (1535 GMT) - Good news for all the cricket fans! The covers are coming off and an inspection is scheduled at 1700 Local (1600 GMT). Stay with us for further updates.
Update 1625 Local (1525 GMT) -  We have an update that the groundsmen are having a look out in the middle as the rain has eased a little. Stay tuned.
Update 1600 Local (1500 GMT) - Unfortunately, it is still raining in Manchester. It does not look we will get back on the field anytime soon. All we can do is wait. Let's hope for the best.

England, on the other hand, have looked poor after Lunch. They gave away too many easy runs and Pakistan feasted on that. Anderson and Broad were poor while Archer got only a few overs to bowl. Bess was good with the ball and he would have had a wicket if Buttler had not dropped a catch, before rain forced the players off. Stay tuned for further updates.

Update 1515 Local (1415 GMT) - Tea has been taken early due to the rain. It was a shortened session which belonged to Pakistan. They came out all guns blazing and have gone to Tea with 8 wickets in hand. Babar Azam was excellent and has counter-attacked since Lunch. Masood has played well too and is reaching his 50.
Update 1505 Local (1405 GMT) - The entire square has been covered now and it looks like it will be a long delay. Stay tuned for further updates.

Update 1450 Local (1350 GMT) - Ohh no! It has gone really gloomy out in the middle and it is drizzling a bit as well. The umpires have decided to take the players off. There was forecast for rain around this time and it has been proven correct. Let's hope that it is not a long delay.
Played that well in the end! Short ball around middle, Babar is late in picking that up but manages to pull it to deep square leg for a couple.

Fifty for Azam! His 14th in Tests. What a player he has become in the last year or so. He's scoring runs just for fun. He did struggle at the start of his innings but then has looked fluent as ever. He gets there by pushing it through covers for one. He would want to keep going here.

England, on the other hand, have looked flat. They erred in their lines and lengths and they have been punished. They could have had Masood but Buttler dropped one down.

Bess could have had Masood not once but twice in the over. Two let offs for the left-hander. Also, Pakistan won't mind seeing the turn on offer for the spinner. Remember, they have two in their side.

We are back for the second session of Day 1. The England players stride out to the middle. Babar Azam and Shan Masood follow them out. Stuart Broad will start with the ball.

England's session to be honest! However, the day started nicely for Pakistan. They won the toss, elected to bat and their openers went about things nicely. They played the new ball well and got through the first hour. However, the introduction of Archer and Woakes changed things. The former got Abid Ali and the latter got the Pakistan skipper. The two did not let the batters score freely too and England would want this to continue after the break. The visitors, on the other hand, would hope that Masood who is doing well out there can continue and hope that someone can give him able support. Do join us at 1340 Local (1240 GMT) for the second session.

We are all in readiness to begin Day 1 of the first Test between England and Pakistan. The England players make their way onto the field, followed by Shan Masood and Abid Ali. James Anderson will start with the ball.
The players from both the sides take a moment of silence in respect of those who have lost their lives due to Covid-19.

Joe Root, the England skipper, says that it was nice to have some time away from the bubble. States that they have made most of their practice period. Adds that they are playing an unchanged squad from the last Test match. Goes on to say that Stokes is not 100 percent fit and they did not want to risk him bowling. Adds that they are aware of not winning the first Test match of a series and they are working hard on improving that.

Azhar Ali, the Pakistan skipper, says that they will bat first. Adds that they wanted to be clear in their heads and they cannot do anything about the weather. States that they are playing 2 spinners with Shadab coming in as an all-rounder. Is thankful to the ECB for providing good facilities to them. Goes on to say that they have prepared themselves well. Adds that they love playing in England and they will miss the crowds.
England (Playing XI) - Rory Burns, Dom Sibley, Joe Root (C), Ben Stokes, Ollie Pope, Jos Buttler (WK), Chris Woakes, Dom Bess, Jofra Archer, Stuart Broad, James Anderson.
Pakistan (Playing XI) - Shan Masood, Abid Ali, Azhar Ali (C), Babar Azam, Asad Shafiq, Mohammad Rizwan (WK), Shadab Khan, Yasir Shah, Mohammad Abbas, Shaheen Afridi, Naseem Shah.
Toss - Up goes the coin and it lands in favour of Pakistan. They have chosen to bat first.

Pakistan, on the other hand, are playing their first Test in the post-Covid era and will look to begin well. They have a good bowling line-up and they will fancy their chances. Their batting is a little weak though and they will want that their batting comes good in testing conditions. They have performed well in England on their last two tours and will look to continue that. Their coach, Misbah-ul-haq, has hinted that they will play 2 spinners, along with 3 pacers. An interesting clash awaits us.

West Indies - checked, Ireland - checked, now it is time for Pakistan to face England, starting with the first Test in Manchester. The home side have lost the first match of a Test series comprising of 2 or more Tests in their last 5 bilateral series and they would want to change that record and start the series with a win. They have named a 14-man squad for this Test and it will be interesting to see who will be the pace bowlers for this game.

Now then, Pakistan would be eager to press home the advantage that their bowlers have given them. They would want to bat and take their lead past a total which one would feel is out of the reach of England. Also, they would hope for the wicket to wear even more so that batting last becomes very difficult. England, on the other hand, need wickets and that too quickly. They will need their star-studded bowling line-up to deliver. Will they do so? We will find out in a bit.

Right from the time they got the cherry in hand, their bowlers were excellent, they took 4 yesterday, with Abbas being the highlight on Day 2. The English batters, Pope and Buttler to be precise, showed some resistance today morning. Pope was the highest scorer for the English with a 50-plus score but they needed a big one from either of him and Buttler. Both though could not make use of the starts they got as one received a jaffa from a 17-year old and the other fell to the guile of Yasir who was the pick of the bowlers. Once Jos fell, the lower order did not contribute a lot, the last 5 wickets were shared between the two leg spinners which has seen Pakistan take a very good lead.

End of a fabulous performance from Pakistan! Once again after a decent session before Lunch, England have crumbled badly in the session which followed. Yasir Shah was the tormentor-in-chief, he bagged 3 out of the five wickets to fall in this session to complete a brilliant performance not only with the ball but in the field too by Pakistan.

The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Attacks the stumps again, Woakes gets right behind the line and plays it to mid off.
Angled into the middle pole, Bess pushes it towards mid on for one.
On middle, Woakes manages to defend it. Another maiden from Shah.
Slider, quicker and on middle, Woakes stays back and defends it onto the ground.
Quicker and outside off, it is left alone.
Shah is bowling with a lot of control here! He floats it up and lands it on off, Woakes is once again solid in defense.
Another tossed up ball on off, CW keeps it out.
Slower through the air and on middle, Woakes prods forward and defends it out.
A bumper to end, it is ducked under.
Shorter and on off, Bess stays back and keeps it out.
Outside off, Bess does not bother playing at it.
Well fielded! On middle, this is clipped nicely towards the mid on fielder. He dived to his right and ensures it is only a single.
Goes short, Woakes pulls it nicely but to the man at mid on.

NOT OUT! Missing leg! Not sure why Pakistan went for the review there. They probably got a little too excited. Naseem Shah too wasn't that interested when he appealed. This is angled into the pads, Woakes looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. An appeal more from the players behind the wicket but it is turned down. Pakistan review. Replays show that they lose one.
Review time! Chris Woakes is the man in question. It looks like it is going down leg. The Ultra Edge shows no bat but the Ball Tracker shows that it is missing the leg stump.
A beauty to end a beautiful over! This is given nice amount of loop and it lands on off, spins away sharply. Bess prods forward to block but is beaten by the away turn.
On middle, Bess gets right behind the line and keeps it out.
One more flighted ball around middle, Bess keeps it out nicely.
Tossed up on off, Bess defends it onto the ground.
Dom Bess is the new batsman in.

OUT! TIMBER! Right through the gate! Yasir Shah strikes on his second ball after Lunch and it is the big one of Buttler. He walks back without adding any runs after the break and he probably takes England's hopes of getting close to the Pakistan total with him. Lovely delivery. Gives it nice amount of loop and lands it on off, Buttler looks to play for turn, he ends up playing outside the line and also leaves the gap between bat and pad. It sneaks it through as it skidded on and clips the off pole. It was the tiniest gap between bat and pad but it goes through. The visitors will be sensing a big lead now.
Flighted ball outside off, Buttler lets it be.
Yasir Shah will bowl from the other end.
A maiden to begin with! On a length and outside off, Woakes lets it be.
Beauty! Goes wide of the crease, it lands on a length, straightens and then zips through. Woakes is squared up as he tries to defend. Gets beaten.
Cracking shot! Fuller and on off, Woakes just puts bat to ball, it races off the willow but straight to the fielder at covers.
Loose! Woakes' patience finally gives in. He gets away with one though. It is another one outside off, wider this time. CW goes after it away from his body but misses.
One more delivery outside off, Woakes does not play at it.
Starts off with one outside off, it is left alone.

We are back for the second session. The Pakistan players are out in the middle. Jos Buttler and Chris Woakes will resume their innings for England. Naseem Shah will start the proceedings for the second session of Day 3.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

Woakes then  came out to bat and seemed uncomfortable to begin with but he looks solid now. Buttler is showing his class by hanging in there but England heavily rely on him at the moment to take them close to Pakistan�s score. The away side will know one more wicket and they are into the bowlers. They would want to take it quickly though. Join us at 1340 Local (1240 GMT) for an intriguing second session.

A testing session of Test cricket comes to an end. It was all about patience for both, the bowlers and the batters. In the end, it will probably be England who will be pleased with how things went along in this one but Pakistan are still ahead in the game. It started off with Pope and Buttler going along things nicely and slowly. The former then got to his half ton but then just as the partnership started to get going, Naseem struck.
Full ball outside off, Buttler makes another leave to the keeper. LUNCH ON DAY 3.
Comes around the wicket and dishes a length ball outside off, Buttler does not fiddle with it as he leaves it alone.
Good length ball outside off, Jos does not bother playing at that one.
Outside off, Buttler has no problems in leaving it alone.
Full ball outside off, Jos shoulders arms to it.
Full ball on off, Buttler drives it to mid off for nothing.
NO BALL! Good length ball on middle, Buttler works it to mid-wicket. Afridi has overstepped.
Quicker ball on off, Woakes defends it out onto the pitch.
Tossed up ball outside off, Woakes leaves it alone.
On off, Chris plays it to cover.
Floated on middle, Woakes pushes it back to the bowler.
Very full ball on off, Buttler pushes it to deep cover for a single.
Flatter ball outside off, Woakes punches it to deep cover for a single.
Outside off, not played at.
Well played! Full delivery on middle, nipping in. Buttler flicks it to fine leg for a couple.
Length ball on off, Jos prods forward and blocks it to mid off.
FOUR! Lovely drive from Buttler! He is looking comfortable now! Full delivery outside off, Buttler drives it through the cover region for a boundary.
On a length outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball outside off, Buttler leaves it alone.
Outside off, Buttler pushes it to deep cover for a single.
Flatter delivery outside off, Buttler lets it go to the keeper.
Flat one outside off, Chris punches it to deep cover for a single.
Short ball around off, Woakes cuts it to point for another dot.
Flatter one on middle, Chris tucks it to mid-wicket.
Starts with a full one outside off, Buttler drives it to deep point for a single.
Yasir Shah comes into the attack. 7-0-36-1 are his figures so far.
Good length ball on middle, Woakes defends it to mid on.
FOUR! This is one of the rare deliveries that Afridi has bowled. It is full and wide. Woakes strides forward and drives it through the cover region for a boundary.
Full ball outside off, Woakes lets it go to the keeper.
EDGY! Good length ball on off, Woakes looks to defend but it takes the edge and goes through the gully region. A couple.
Great news! The rain has stopped and the players are back on the field. This was quick. Shaheen Afridi will finish his over.

Well, well, well, it is raining! Did not see that coming, the forecast was for no rain but it has arrived. The Manchester weather has always been fickle and it has been proven right here. It though seems to be a passing shower, let�s hope it is one. Stay tuned.
FOUR! Poor fielding! Abbas was maybe tired after bowling a long spell. Full ball on middle, Woakes drives it past the bowler. Abbas chases after it and tumbles but fails to stop it. Four signalled.

An appeal for LBW turned down! Probably going down leg! Good length ball on middle and leg, angling in. Woakes looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pad. There is an appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire. Pakistan think of a review but decide against it.
On middle, defended nicely.
Good length and outside off, not played at.
FOUR! Away from the body but gets the desired result! Fuller and outside off, tailing away. Buttler reaches out for it. It goes uppishly but wide of point and for a boundary.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
SHOT! This should give him some confidence. Another length delivery on off, Woakes strokes it on the up through covers and takes three.
A short leg fielder comes in place now.

That is a gem! But Chris Woakes seemed like he was actually backing away before the ball was even bowled. Maybe he was worried about another short ball. Shah though lands it on a length and around off, it pitches and straightens. Woakes ends up pushing at it tentatively away from his body. Gets beaten.
The batsman chooses to leave the ball outside his off stump.
One more ball outside off, it is not played at.
Closer to the off pole but not close enough to make the batter play.

WIDE! Way too short and well outside off, Buttler leaves. It keeps going with the angle after it passes the batter. Rizwan does well to move to his right and take it with one hand diving to that direction.
Outside off, left alone.
Uppish but for two! Fuller and around off, Buttler plays a check-drive, it goes wide of the bowler and down towards long off for two.
Good length and on middle, defended.

Mandatory concussion Test! Woakes was hit on the helmet and the umpires have called for the physio. Woakes wants a new helmet. Chris seems fine though and that is a good sign. Shaheen Afridi is back into the attack. 13-4-18-1 are his figures so far.

Right on the helmet! Welcome to the crease Woakes! This is shorter and on middle, Woakes is a touch late in ducking under it. He is hit on the helmet. Seems a little rattled as he stays in the ducked position for a bit but seems fine now. End of a steamy over from Naseem.
Back of a length and on middle, defended nicely.
Good length and on off, kept out.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! That is a nasty delivery! Top class from Naseem Shah. Pope is in disbelief! He couldn't do a lot over there. Needed something good to get rid of Pope who was looking solid and Shah has provided it. He is absolutely pumped up. A real effort ball. It lands on a length and around off, takes off from nowhere. Pope does all he could to keep it down. He looks to play it with soft hands and also tries taking one hand off the handle in the end. Nothing saves him as the ball keeps rising, hits the shoulder of the bat and lobs towards gully. Shadab takes it quite awkwardly. He had his body weight backwards but did well to hang onto it. He then indicates he did not see it. An important catch though as the momentum had just about started to shift. England trail by 199.
Chris Woakes is the next man in.
Drags his length back and the line is a little straighter. It is worked towards mid-wicket.
FOUR! Delightful! Easy! Full and outside off, Pope leans into it and creams it through covers for a boundary.
On a length on off, Pope pushes it to point and takes off for a run. Buttler hesitates but decides to go for it. They make it easily in the end.
FOUR! Width and dealt with ease! Good length ball outside off, Pope drives it with superb timing through the cover region for a boundary.
Quick single! Full delivery on middle,  Buttler works it to mid on and takes a single.
Full ball outside off, Buttler lets it go to the keeper. Rizwan dives to his right and collects it well. Excellent keeping.
Good length ball on off, Buttler blocks it to cover.
NO BALL! Full ball on off, Pope pushes it towards cover-point and takes a single. The third umpire conveys it to the on-field umpire that Abbas has overstepped.
On a length on middle, Pope works it to square leg.
Good length ball outside off, Jos makes another leave.
Outside off, not played at it again.
On a length outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball on middle, pushed back to the bowler.

FOUR! That is a gorgeous shot! That will give him a lot of confidence! Full delivery outside off, Buttler lunges forward and times it beautifully through extra cover for a boundary. 50-run stand comes up between the two. Brilliant one for the hosts. They have weathered the first hour well and need to continue.
Full ball on middle and leg, Buttler blocks it to mid on.

DRINKS! An excellent hour of play for both sides! Pakistan did not give many runs and their fast bowlers were right on the money and they kept it tight. England, on the other hand, would be pleased that they haven't lost a wicket despite a few passing the edge. They will look to consolidate from here on and not throw away their wickets.
Fullish on off, Pope pushes it to point.

Was there an edge? The keeper certainly thinks so. Good length ball outside off, Pope attempts to defend but misses. The keeper does well to collect it and appeals for caught behind. Nothing from the umpire though.
On a length outside off, Pope lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball on off, Pope blocks it to cover.
On a length on off, solidly blocked to mid off.
BEATEN! Lovely delivery from Abbas! Good length ball outside off, Pope looks to push at it but fails to make any connection.
Good length ball outside off, Jos lets it go to the keeper.
Fullish on middle, Jos taps it to the point region.
Good length ball on off, Jos defends it to cover.
On a length outside off, Buttler makes another leave.
Good length ball outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to it.
Full delivery on middle, Pope flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
On off, Buttler solidly blocks it out onto the pitch.
FOUR BYES! The keeper is not getting that! A big in-swinger from Abbas on the pads, Buttler looks to flick but misses. Rizwan dives to his left but misses. The ball goes into the fine leg fence.
Goes full this time and bowls it on off, Jos strides forward and drives it to mid off.
On a length on off, Jos blocks it to point for another dot.
Abbas bowls a length ball outside off, Buttler covers his stumps and lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Buttler blocks it to cover off the back foot.
Good length ball outside off, Pope leaves it alone.
Outside off, left alone by Pope.
BEATEN! Wow, what a beauty from Naseem! There is a good battle going on between Naseem and Pope! Length ball outside off, Pope looks to defend but misses it completely.
On a length on middle, Pope works it to mid-wicket.
Top class stuff from Naseem! Pakistan have done well with the ball in the morning session! Good length ball outside off, Pope looks to defend but fails to get any bat on it.
Good length ball on off, Pope defends it to the cover region.
BEATEN AGAIN! Top, top stuff from Abbas! On a length and around off, it pitches and moves away. Buttler looks to defend but gets beaten.
Goes wide of the crease now, maybe to create an angle or to stay away from the danger zone. It is outside off, left alone.
On middle, it is kept out. The umpire just having a look at where Abbas finishes with his followthrough, whether he is stepping on the danger area, no warning or word for now.
Angled into the pads, Buttler looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.

That is a peach! Just too good! Buttler could only hope for it to miss the outside edge. It lands on off and it is on a length which means Buttler has to play at it. He looks to defend but the ball leaves him and whizzes past the outside edge.
Angled into the off pole, it pitches and then leaves the batter. Beats the outside edge of Buttler's bat. Good delivery again.
That's a loose, loose shot from Pope! He would be disappointed by that! Good length ball outside off, Pope looks to drive but fails to make any connection with it.
Nice looking drive! Full ball outside off, Buttler leans forward and creams the drive through extra cover. Three taken before the fielder cuts it off. First runs for Jos in 30 balls.
Fullish delivery on off, Buttler prods forward and pushes it to cover.

Just short! The first slip fielder is standing a little behind! This though is a loose shot from Jos Buttler! Back of a length ball outside off, Buttler looks to punch it off the back foot but it takes the edge and goes towards first slip. It lands in front of the fielder at first slip.
Good length ball outside off, Buttler has no problems in leaving it alone.
Naseem starts with a full delivery on off, at 142 kph. Buttler strides forward and pushes it to mid off.
Naseem Shah is into the attack for the first time on Day 3.
On the stumps to end, defended nicely.
Another one outside off, left alone.
One more delivery outside off, not played at.
Attacks the off pole, blocked out.
Just outside off, Pope does not play at it.
Outside off, not played at.
On middle, Buttler defends it out nicely.
Good running! Such quick singles are important when runs are not coming easily. On middle, it is pushed towards mid on for one.
Outside off, left alone.

Good stop! Good work from Pakistan in the field! They are making England work hard for their runs which will just keep building the pressure. Full and on off, Pope strokes it to the right of mid off where the fielder dives and stops it.
Fuller and on off, it tails back in a touch. Pope strokes it to mid on.
Another inside edge! Maybe Pope is just going at it a little too hard. It is full and outside off, Pope looks to hit it through the off side but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Outside off, not played at.
On a length outside off, Buttler does not bother playing at that one.
Fullish ball on off, Jos pushes it to mid off for another dot.
On a length on off, Buttler blocks it to cover.

FOUR BYES! Poor keeping from Rizwan! Should have stopped that! Good length ball outside off, Buttler looks to defend but misses. The keeper fails to collect and the ball goes to the third man fence. 100 up.
EDGED BUT JUST SHORT! Good length ball on off, Buttler looks to defend but gets an outside edge. Luckily for him, it lands short of the second slip fielder.
The sucker ball to end, full and wide outside off. Pope is not sucked into the shot. He leaves it alone.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length and on off, blocked.
Fuller and outside off, Pope goes after it a little too hard. He gets an inside edge onto the leg side. Afridi has overstepped as the third umpire conveys the message to the on-field umpire.

FIFTY FOR POPE! His 5th in Tests! Quality, quality knock till now! He thrived under testing conditions yesterday against bowlers who were brilliant. Also, he was under pressure when he walked out but he has come good. Needs to keep going though. He gets there by working it through square leg and bags a couple.

It bounces over the stumps! Pope probably decided to play that really late and that could have cost him. It is on a length and just outside off. Pope looks to play it late but gets an inside edge which bounces in front of the stumps and then goes over it.
Another dot! Fuller and around off, Pope looks to hit it through the off side but it goes off the inner half towards mid on.
A fuller ball to end! JB strokes it towards mid on. The fielder there moves to his left quickly and stops it. Good energy shown by Pakistan in the field. They aren't letting England score easily.
Outside off, not played at.

BEATEN! This is what Abbas can do. He would land it on a length and the line is around that off pole and get it to move both the ways. This time he gets it to straighten. Buttler does nothing wrong as he tries to play the original line but is beaten.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length and on middle, kept out.
Pope probably misses out on one there! It is angled into the pads, Pope works it nicely but too close to mid on for one.
This one comes back in just a little after landing on middle, Buttler works it to mid-wicket.
Once again hits the length and the off stump is attacked. Buttler goes back and keeps it solidly.
Another delivery on a length and on the stumps, defended nicely.

Quick run! Afridi gets this one full and around off, Pope pushes it to mid off and takes off. The fielder does have a shy at the bowler's end but misses. Pope's dive would have saved him though. The batsmen cross ends.
Another leave as it is once again bowled outside off.
Just outside off, Afridi is looking to get the ball back in. It goes on with the angle. Left alone.
Good length ball on middle, Buttler solidly blocks it to mid-wicket.
On a length outside off, Buttler makes a leave to this one.
Full ball on off, Buttler prods forward and defends it to cover.
Good length ball outside off, moving away. Buttler lets it through to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Buttler solidly defends it to mid on.
Abbas starts with an out-swinging good length delivery outside off, Buttler leaves it alone.
Mohammad Abbas will bowl from the other end.
Good start from Afridi! Good length ball on off, Ollie pushes it to mid off to get through the over.
Another length ball outside off, Pope shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball on middle, Pope flicks it to mid-wicket.
NO BALL! Shaheen oversteps! Good length on off, Pope solidly blocks it to cover.
Full ball on off, Pope prods forward and pushes it to the mid off region for a dot.
Good length ball on off, angling in. Pope camps on his back foot and pushes it to gully.
Afridi starts with a good length ball down the leg side, Pope leaves it alone.

We are all set to begin Day 3! The Pakistan players make their way out to the middle, followed by Ollie Pope and Jos Buttler. 98 overs are scheduled to be bowled today, weather permitting. Shaheen Afridi will start with the ball.
Weather report - The sun is out and that is a good sign for all the cricket fans. Let's hope that the rain gods stay away and do not spoil the party.

England, on the other hand, need Pope and Buttler to build a strong partnership and reduce the trail. They have only the bowlers to come after this and they don't want a wicket to fall early. An exciting day awaits us.

Day 3 is called the moving day and this Test match has moved pretty quickly on Day 2. Pakistan inched ahead courtesy a fine batting performance from Masood and then their bowlers were exceptional, reducing the hosts to 92/4. They would now hope to pick up wickets quickly and get a good lead.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...
The first session on Day 3 can well decide which way this game is going. Do join us at 1100 Local (1000 GMT) to find out.

Pope though is doing really well. He is 4 short of a half ton and Buttler has started off well. They need to continue though as England still trail by another 234 runs. Pakistan know another wicket and they will be into the bowling all-rounders. They would hope for more of the same from their bowlers.

Pakistan's session, Pakistan's day! They are well ahead in the game at the moment! They had a hero with the bat in Masood and heroes with the ball in Abbas, Afridi and Yasir. Afridi started things by getting rid of Burns. Then Abbas took over and picked up Sibley and Stokes. Root then tried to weather the storm but he fell prey to Yasir.
Flighted outside off, Buttler leaves it alone. STUMPS ON DAY 2.
Flatter one on middle, Pope flicks it to deep square leg for a single.

NOT OUT! Buttler is well in! The umpire probably wanted to be sure! Floated ball on middle, Pope comes down the track and pushes it back to the bowler. Shah gets a hand on it and it rolls onto the stumps. Pakistan appeal and the umpire takes it upstairs. The replays roll in and they show that Buttler was well in.
An appeal for run out. It has been taken upstairs. Yasir has gotten hands to it but Buttler is well in.
Loopy delivery on off, Pope pushes it to point.
Flighted delivery on off, Pope plays it to covers.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Pope defends it off the back foot.
Good length ball on off, Buttler blocks it to point.
Good shot for nothing! Full delivery on middle, Buttler drives it with power but straight back to the bowler.
Good length ball on off, Ollie pushes it to cover and takes a single.
On a length on off, Pope defends it to mid off.
Good length ball outside off, Ollie leaves it alone.
Very full delivery outside off, Pope lets it go to the keeper.
Outside off, not played at.
This time behind square! Short ball outside off, Buttler cuts it behind square on the off side and picks up a couple.
FOUR! That is exceptionally well timed! Flatter one outside off, Buttler moves inside his crease and drives it through the cover region for a boundary.
Tosses this one on middle, Pope uses his feet and drives it to mid off for a single.
Flatter ball outside off, Pope lets it go to the keeper.
Floated on middle, Pope defends it to short leg.
Good length ball on middle, Buttler tucks it to mid-wicket.
On a length on the pads, Buttler looks to flick but gets hit on the pads. There is a mild appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire.
Good length delivery on middle, Jos blocks it to mid on.
On a length outside off, Buttler makes another leave to the keeper.
Outside off, not played at.
Good length ball outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to it.
The batsman plays it with an angled bat and guides it to third man. The batsmen have run through for a single.
That nearly took the off stump! Loopy ball on middle, Buttler looks to defend but it spins away and beats the edge. It goes just over the off stump.
Close! Floated outside off, Buttler looks to leave. The ball goes just past the off stump.
Full on off, Pope dances down the track and drives it to mid off for a quick single.
Loopy ball outside off, Pope shoulders arms to it.
Flatter on middle, Pope flicks it to deep square leg and picks up a couple.
FOUR! That's a poor delivery and it is beautifully played by Jos Buttler! Fullish on off, Buttler creams the drive through mid off for a boundary.
Outside off, not played at.
Fullish ball outside off, Buttler does not play at that one.
Good length ball outside off, Buttler leaves it alone.
Good length ball down the leg side, Buttler looks to flick but misses.
Good length ball on the pads, Pope looks to defend. It goes off his thigh pad towards deep square leg. A leg bye taken.
Shaheen Afridi is back into the attack. 6-3-7-1 are his figures so far.
Flatter one outside off, Buttler lets it go to the keeper.
Low full toss on middle, Jos paddles it to fine leg for another couple.
Flighted ball on middle, Buttler paddle sweeps it to fine leg for a couple. Buttler is off the mark.
On middle, Buttler defends it back to the bowler.
Low full toss on off, Buttler drives it to cover. It ricochets off the fielder towards mid off. No run though.
Loopy ball on off, Buttler prods forward and defends it to cover.
Good length ball on off, Pope defends it out.

FOUR! Slashes and slashes hard! There is a good battle going on between Naseem and Pope. Full ball outside off, Pope looks to slash but it takes the edge and goes past the gully fielder and into the fence.
FOUR! Pope is a good player and shows it again. Short delivery on off, Pope pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Short delivery outside off, Pope sways away from it.
Good length delivery on middle, Pope offers a solid block on this one.
On a good length on off, Pope defends it off the back foot.
Loopy ball on middle, Buttler defends it back to the bowler.
Jos Buttler makes his way out to the middle.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Root falls and Pakistan strike again! Yasir Shah did not start well but has delivered the wicket. Root was struggling at the crease and his luck runs out. Brilliant catch from Rizwan though. Flatter one around off, Root looks to cut but it is too close. It takes the outside edge towards the keeper. Rizwan takes a good catch. England have a long tail and they desperately did not want this wicket to fall. Pakistan are on top at the moment.

Short and outside off, Pope cuts it through point for a single. 50-run partnership between Pope and Root. A much-needed partnership for England. They were in trouble early on and this has settled the nerves a little bit.
Floated delivery on off, Root plays it towards point. The batsmen cross ends.
Flighted delivery on off, Root looks to drive but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Root flicks it through square leg. The batsmen get two runs.

An appeal for LBW! Good length ball on off, angling in. Pope looks to leave it but the ball comes in and hits him on the pads. Naseem appeals but nothing from the umpire. Good decision not to review as the Ball Tracker shows that it was missing the stumps.
PLAY AND A MISS! Extra effort ball from Naseem! Short ball outside off, Pope looks to play the cut but the ball beats the bat and goes into the mitts of the keeper.
On a length on off, Ollie solidly blocks it to mid off.
Length ball on off, Pope blocks it to cover off the front foot.
Good length ball on middle, Pope pushes it to mid on.
Short ball outside off, Pope sways away from it.
FOUR! Yasir Shah is leaking runs here! Floated on middle, Root paddle sweeps it to the fine leg region for a boundary.
Short one outside off, Joe punches it to point.
Tossed up outside off, Root leaves it alone.
Good batting! Floated ball on middle, Pope comes down the track and flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Hammered! 50 up in style! Short ball on middle, Pope moves inside the crease and then pulls it to the deep square leg region for a boundary.
Flatter ball outside off, Pope cuts it straight to point.
Back of a length on off, Root blocks it to point.
Short ball outside off, at 144 kph. Root looks to play at it first but moves his bat away.
Full ball on off, Root strides forward and plays it to mid off.
On a length on off, Root blocks it to cover off the back foot.
Good length ball on middle, Pope works it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Pope is a class player and it shows in this shot! Full delivery outside off, Pope lunges forward and drives it through the cover region for a boundary.
FOUR! That will break the shackles! Loopy ball on middle, Root goes on his knees and then sweeps it to the deep square leg region for a boundary.
The batsman shoulders arms to let that one through.
Massive turn! Loopy ball outside off, Root looks to defend but the ball spins away and beats the bat.

A big appeal for LBW! Probably going down leg. Floated ball on the pads, Root looks to defend but gets rapped on the pads. Pakistan appeal but the umpire is not interested. The Ball Tracker shows that it was pitching outside leg.
Loopy ball on off, Pope drives it through the covers for a single.
Shah starts with a loosener on the pads, Pope pulls it to deep square leg for a couple.
Spin time! Yasir Shah is into the attack.
On a length on middle and leg, Root defends it to mid on.
Good length ball on middle, Pope flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Classic shot from Pope! Brilliant! Full ball on middle, Pope drives it through mid on for a boundary.
Good length ball down the leg side, Pope looks to flick but fails to make any connection.
Full ball on middle, Ollie pushes it to mid on.
On a length on middle at 143 kph. Pope solidly plays it back to the bowler.
On middle, solidly defended to silly mid off.
Good length ball outside off, Root shoulders arms to it.
On a length on off, Joe punches it to cover.
Good length ball on middle, Root is solid in defense.

The spinners will be eager to bowl again, judging by the spin that this pitch has offered so far. This might be the last day of the Test as well. Do join us in a while.

Welcome everyone! England have made a roaring comeback in this game but they still have a long way to go. First, they need to pick up the two remaining wickets as quickly as possible and then bat better than they did in the first innings. It won't be easy against the bowling of Pakistan on this wicket which has started to take some serious turn and bounce and they have two quality spinners in the line-up. They would hope that they play their best level of cricket and take a 1-0 lead.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Pakistan, on the other hand, will be pleased with where they stand in the game! However, they were unable to push home the advantage that they got after bowling out England earlier on in the day courtesy Yasir Shah's four-fer. They though would know that this is not a lead which is daunting but on this wicket and with the bowlers they have, they will back themselves to defend it. They though will somehow hope the last two wickets can drag this lead to over 260. Anything above 255 or 260 will give them that psychological edge. Day 4 promises to be a cracker, it could well be the last day of the Test too. Do join us for all the action at 1100 Local (1000 GMT). Until then, cheers.

That's all from this game! England have come back from behind and won their first game of a three-match series after a long time. They have also received 40 points in the ICC World Test Championship. Pakistan, on the other hand, will need to recover from this loss quickly and perform better in crunch situations. The next Test begins on 13th August, 2020 at 1100 Local (1000 GMT) in Southampton. Until then, cheers and take care.

Chris Woakes, the MAN OF THE MATCH, says playing positive was the way to go especially after Pope fell and he talked to Buttler about it. Adds that the idea to take it to Pakistan worked and seeing Jos Buttler bat like that was good. Says that it was a great partnership and Jos is one of the best white-ball players in the world and he showed that he can play well in Tests too. Goes onto say that he has been working hard in the nets and tried to get into form. States that he focussed on the ball and luckily, it worked. Is pleased to take the wickets of the big chaps in the Pakistan team as they can do a lot of damage.

Joe Root, the England skipper, says that it was a fantastic Test match and brilliant cricket was played for all the four days. Adds that Woakes and Buttler were pretty clever with how they played. States that it took something special but they believed that anything can happen and they never gave up. Says that Buttler did really well and he managed the risks well and how he played the spinners was fantastic to see. Adds that they need to back up their performance but realizes that they need to improve on certain aspects of the game.

Azhar Ali, the Pakistan skipper, says that it was a wonderful Test but is disappointed to be on the wrong end of it. Credits Woakes and Buttler for playing really  well and they changed the momentum of the game. Adds that when someone plays like that, it is difficult to set fields. States that this innings from Woakes and Buttler was not far from how Stokes played against Australia last year. Goes on to say that they would have enjoyed more with the crowds. Says that it was a surprise that the ball did not reverse later on. States that they had the opportunity to bat England out of the game but suddenly they lost wickets and it is unfortunate not to get more runs on the board. Ends by saying that they should have defended this total.
Stay tuned for the Presentation ceremony as we find out who the Man of the Match is.

277 though still seemed a little out of reach for England on this wicket. The feeling was proving to be correct when they were five down for 117. One partnership though, one brilliant stand, two excellent individually brilliant knocks has taken them over the line. The visitors' bowlers were excellent till the Buttler-Woakes stand. The younger ones, the ones who lacked experience, probably crumbled under pressure and had no answers to the counterattack from the two. Yasir Shah, the experienced campaigner, once again impressed with a four-fer but he lacked support when needed. In the end, this could well be termed as a demoralizing loss.

For Pakistan, this is going to be a difficult loss to take. They would have felt in control of this Test right from the first day when Masood�s marathon innings took them to a competitive total. Then, Yasir�s four-fer saw them bundle out England for 107 runs less than what they scored in their first innings. England did fight back with the ball as a combined effort saw them bowl Pakistan out for 169.

Time for the final session of Day 4 and maybe the match! The Pakistan players stride out to the middle, followed by Jos Buttler and Chris Woakes. 110 runs more to win for England. Mohammad Abbas will start with the ball.

Pakistan's session easily but the partnership between Buttler and Woakes just gives a sense of the momentum shifting in favour of England. Pakistan is still on top but this stand might just be getting them worried. However, they were excellent right from the word go after Lunch. They got wickets once again at regular intervals and have got rid of the top and the middle order of the England side. They would know another two wickets or so and they would be into the tail. However, Buttler and Woakes are looking pretty comfortable out there especially the latter who has come out with a lot more intent. They need to go on for longer. Another 110 runs are needed and they would want this pair to score as much as possible. Can they do so, can they continue the fightback? We will find out after the break.

50-run stand comes up! Short ball on middle, Buttler pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single. Excellent counterattacking cricket from England. They are in still with a chance, courtesy this partnership. TEA ON DAY 4.

All set for the second session of Day 4! The Pakistan players make their way out to the middle, followed by Joe Root and Dom Sibley. They need 222 runs more to win. Mohammad Abbas will start with the ball for the visiting side.
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

So, England have started their chase quite nicely! Yes, they have lost Burns but Root and Sibley have then looked to steady things and are now looking comfortable out there. However, there is still a long way to go and it will be vital for the hosts for the two to make use of the starts they have got. Pakistan, on the other hand, have bowled decently. They have hit the right lines and lengths on most of the occasions but the key here is to be patient and one feels, they would get the rewards. However, the first sessions in this Test have mostly been good for the English. It is the second session where they falter. They can't afford that now so it will be interesting to see how they go about things. Join us at 1340 Local (1240 GMT) for the second session.
